# Tile Caching Implementation Plan

To make the tile rendering extremely fast, we can implement Edge Caching (via CDN) and Client-Side Browser caching. Because the DuckDB query `ST_AsMVT` computes geometry heavily on the fly, avoiding hitting the backend for the same tile is critical for map performance.

## Proposed Changes

We will modify the Flask service to add appropriate HTTP headers.

### [app.py](file:///c:/Users/kavya/Downloads/PROJECTS/nyc_building_explorer/app.py)

#### [MODIFY] [app.py](file:///c:/Users/kavya/Downloads/PROJECTS/nyc_building_explorer/app.py)(file:///c:/Users/kavya/Downloads/PROJECTS/nyc_building_explorer/app.py)
Update the [get_tile](file:///c:/Users/kavya/Downloads/PROJECTS/nyc_building_explorer/app.py#19-46) route to append a `Cache-Control` header to the response.

```python
# Before
return flask.Response(tile, mimetype='application/x-protobuf')

# After
response = flask.Response(tile, mimetype='application/x-protobuf')
# Cache publicly for 24 hours (86400 seconds)
# This tells browsers AND edge CDNs (like Cloudflare, Nginx, Varnish) to cache the tile
response.headers['Cache-Control'] = 'public, max-age=86400' 
return response
```

> [!TIP]
> If you deploy this behind a CDN (like Cloudflare) or an Nginx reverse proxy, the `public` directive ensures the proxy caches the `.pbf` files at the edge. This means 99% of users panning around the map will never actually hit your Python DuckDB server.

## Verification Plan

### Manual Verification
1. Open the browser's Developer Tools (Network Tab).
2. Pan the map.
3. Select a `.pbf` network request.
4. Verify the Response Headers contain `Cache-Control: public, max-age=86400`.
5. Pan away and pan back to the same spot; verify the network request shows [(disk cache)](file:///c:/Users/kavya/Downloads/PROJECTS/nyc_building_explorer/app.py#282-285) or [(memory cache)](file:///c:/Users/kavya/Downloads/PROJECTS/nyc_building_explorer/app.py#282-285) instead of hitting the server again.
